Architecture plan for Issues #23-#32: alex-0d18-test-8 gameplay layer

Current foundation:
- The product name is `alex-0d18-test-8` per PRODUCT.md.
- The app is a Vite + TypeScript full-window canvas game foundation.
- Existing modules provide `GameLoop`, `KeyboardInput`, `SceneManager`,
  `Entity`, `EntityManager`, AABB collision helpers, sprite/fallback rendering,
  `TileGrid`, tile types, and brick quadrant damage.
- Tests use Vitest beside source files as `*.test.ts`.

Module structure and file organization:
- Keep `src/main.ts` as bootstrap only. Gameplay orchestration should move into
  scene or domain modules instead of growing inside the entrypoint.
- Add `src/entities/Tank.ts` for shared tank behavior: position/size, direction,
  speed, HP, faction/owner, movement intent, collision box, and optional reload
  state.
- Add `src/entities/PlayerTank.ts` for player-specific input mapping, lives,
  respawn state if needed, and player firing constraints.
- Add `src/entities/EnemyTank.ts` for enemy variants. Define `EnemyTankType`
  configs for basic, fast, and armored speed/HP/score values.
- Add `src/entities/Bullet.ts` for bullet position, direction, speed, owner
  faction/id, damage, and screen/world bounds despawn.
- Add lightweight effect entities in `src/entities/Explosion.ts` and
  `src/entities/SpawnFlash.ts`, or a shared timed-effect base if duplication
  becomes meaningful.
- Add `src/entities/PowerUp.ts` for power-up type, duration, pickup collision,
  and rendering metadata.
- Add `src/game/` for gameplay coordination that should not live on individual
  entities:
  - `movement.ts`: grid-aligned movement helpers and tile/entity blocking.
  - `combat.ts`: bullet creation, bullet-vs-terrain, bullet-vs-tank, scoring,
    friendly-fire filtering, and explosion spawning.
  - `enemyAi.ts`: pure enemy decision function with deterministic RNG input.
  - `spawner.ts`: spawn queue, spawn-point rotation, concurrent enemy cap, and
    spawn flash timing.
  - `powerUps.ts`: effect application and duration ticking.
  - `levelState.ts`: level complete, base destroyed, lives exhausted, and
    scene-change event calculation.
- Add `src/levels/` for level data and loading:
  - `LevelTypes.ts`: level schema, spawn config, enemy wave entries, and map
    symbol definitions.
  - `LevelLoader.ts`: parse/validate level data into `TileGrid` plus spawn
    config and player/base spawn positions.
  - `levels.ts` or JSON assets for three starter levels.
- Add `src/game/GameScene.ts` once gameplay needs a scene owner. It should own
  the `TileGrid`, `EntityManager`, level state, spawner, input, update order,
  and render order.

Shared types:
- Reuse `Vector2` and `Direction` from `src/entities/Entity.ts`.
- Reuse `AABB` helpers from `src/physics/aabb.ts`; add small conversion helpers
  such as `entityToAabb(entity)` only if repeated code appears.
- Use `Faction = 'player' | 'enemy'` or equivalent for bullet ownership and
  friendly-fire checks.
- Treat `dt` as seconds in all entity and game update APIs.
- Keep world coordinates in pixels and tile coordinates as integer grid indices.
- Keep level dimensions compatible with `TileGrid` and existing tile constants.

Dependencies between issues:
- #32 Player tank movement should land early because bullets, pickups, lives,
  and game-over state all depend on a player entity. It depends on existing
  input, entity, tile, and collision foundations.
- #23 Bullet entity and firing depends on #32 or at least a tank firing API.
  Implement reload cooldown and max active bullets through shared tank/combat
  helpers so enemies can reuse the same firing path later.
- #24 Bullet-vs-terrain collision depends on #23 and existing tile/brick damage.
  It should mutate bricks through `TileGrid.damageQuadrant`, stop at steel, pass
  water/grass, destroy the base, and despawn bullets on hit.
- #26 Enemy tank entity and types can share the tank base from #32/#23. It
  establishes enemy HP, movement speed, score value, and power-up flags.
- #25 Tank-vs-bullet collision depends on #23 and #26/#32. It applies damage,
  removes defeated enemies, decrements player lives, awards score, filters
  friendly fire, and spawns explosions.
- #27 Enemy AI depends on #26. Keep the decision function pure and unit-tested:
  choose directions, react to blocked movement or timers, aim toward player/base
  when aligned, and request firing without directly mutating entities.
- #31 Level loader depends on `TileGrid` and should be implemented before wave
  completion is finalized. It provides map layout, base/player spawn, top spawn
  points, and enemy wave data.
- #28 Enemy spawner depends on #26 and #31. It consumes the level wave list,
  spawns from configured top points, caps concurrent enemies around four, and
  adds a brief spawn flash.
- #30 Power-ups depend on #26 and #32. Specially flagged enemies can drop
  entities; player overlap applies extra life, base shield, weapon upgrade, or
  enemy freeze with durations where applicable.
- #29 Level completion and game-over conditions depends on #24/#25/#28/#31. It
  advances when the wave pool is exhausted and all enemies are gone, and emits
  game-over scene changes when the base is destroyed or lives reach zero.

Key design decisions:
- Build one shared tank movement/firing model and specialize it through player,
  enemy, and AI modules. That avoids duplicating collision, facing, and reload
  logic.
- Keep AI, level parsing, collision resolution, spawner state, and win/loss
  checks mostly pure so each issue can add focused Vitest coverage without
  requiring a running canvas.
- Use the existing `EntityManager` for runtime entities but add typed query
  helpers locally in `GameScene` or `game/` modules instead of changing the base
  manager unless repeated casts become a problem.
- Render in layers: base tiles, non-overlay entities/effects, grass overlay
  tiles, then HUD/debug overlays if added later.
- Treat terrain as authoritative for blocking and projectile interaction:
  brick/steel/base block tanks, water blocks tanks but not bullets, grass is an
  overlay, map edges block everything.
- Prefer compact JSON level objects with an ASCII map string array plus explicit
  wave entries. ASCII keeps maps readable; JSON carries typed spawn and wave
  metadata.
- Keep issue work independently mergeable. Each issue should add tests for its
  new logic and avoid broad rewrites outside the modules it owns.
